-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Evaluate the Ackermann-type function f at the point (4, 1981). 2. [Key Idea] Identify f with the classical Ackermann function A(x,y); then use the known closed forms A(3,y)=2^{\,y+3}-3 and A(4,y)=2↑↑(y+3)-3 (a tower of y+3 twos). 3. [Proof] Step 0 (Ackermann identification) The three given rules are exactly the defining recurrence of A(x,y); hence f≡A. Step 1 (small first arguments – routine induction) A(0,y)=y+1 A(1,y)=y+2 A(2,y)=2y+3 A(3,y)=2^{\,y+3}-3 (1) Step 2 (first argument 4) Set g(y)=A(4,y). Initial value: g(0)=A(3,1)=2^{4}-3=13. Recurrence from the definition: g(y+1)=A(3,g(y))=2^{\,g(y)+3}-3. (2) Claim by induction: g(y)=2↑↑(y+3)-3, i.e. a power-tower of 2’s of height y+3 minus 3. • Base y=0: 2↑↑3=2^{2^{2}}=16 ⇒ 16−3=13=g(0). • Inductive step: suppose g(y)=2↑↑(y+3)-3; then g(y+1)=2^{\,g(y)+3}-3 =2^{\,(2↑↑(y+3)-3)+3}-3 =2^{\,2↑↑(y+3)}-3 =2↑↑(y+4)-3, so the formula holds. Step 3 (desired value) Insert y=1981: f(4,1981)=A(4,1981)=2↑↑(1981+3)−3=2↑↑1984−3, i.e. a stack of 1984 twos, each serving as the exponent of the one below, minus three. 4. [Conclusion] f(4,1981) equals 2↑↑1984 − 3, a power-tower of 1984 twos with 3 subtracted.
